data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 with no migration needed.

That said, modern .NET idiom would favor `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` with `CancellationToken` over manual threads:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, ct, async (item, token) =>
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation support if you need it later. But your current code will compile and run on .NET 8 as-is.
